YOUR TASK

Complete ALL EXECUTION PLAN tasks before stopping.

Implementation checklist:
- Follow existing project patterns and neighboring files.
- Make the smallest self-contained change that solves the problem.
- Avoid unrelated cleanup, broad restyling, or repo-wide churn unless the task truly requires it.
- Verify dependencies before using new libraries or APIs.
- Detect and use the repository's native formatter, linter, type checker, test runner, and build checks.
- A finished change should leave behind a quality gate you would trust: runnable linting, testing, and static verification appropriate to the language/framework.
- When that baseline does not exist yet, establish the ecosystem's best-practice baseline yourself instead of shipping without it, and err toward stronger standard linting rules over weaker ones.
- Make casual bypasses visible in that gate when the ecosystem supports it, such as broad lint disables, blanket type suppressions, weakened assertions, or skipped failing paths.
- Never weaken quality gates to get green: do not disable tests, bypass lint rules, widen suppressions, loosen types, reduce assertion strength, or skip failing paths unless the request explicitly requires that tradeoff.
- If a suppression is truly unavoidable, keep it local to the narrowest scope, explain it inline, and prefer a real fix, adapter, wrapper, or refactor first.
- Prefer testable design: use dependency injection, explicit seams, pure logic, and boundary extraction instead of hard-wiring time, filesystem, network, environment, process, singleton, or framework globals into core logic.
- If tests are hard to write or require real external I/O for routine coverage, treat that as a design smell and refactor toward deterministic tests with mocks, fakes, or injected boundaries where appropriate.
- Prefer straightforward, maintainable code over clever tricks or premature abstraction.
- Keep interfaces narrow and explicit so behavior stays easy to understand, test, and change safely.
- Add dependencies, abstractions, or layers only when they clearly reduce complexity or improve correctness, testability, or maintainability.
- For behavior changes and bug fixes, add or update tests in the same change.
- Fix root causes, not surface-level symptoms.
- Keep scope on requested work unless your instructions require otherwise.
- Re-check the ORIGINAL REQUEST and confirm acceptance criteria are met.
- Do not claim completion until the relevant verification commands actually pass.
